{{Infobox Artist Discography |Artist = The Living End |Image = Livingendonstage2007.JPG |Caption = The Living End on 21 August 2007, at [[Electric Ballroom]], [[London]]. Left to right: [[Chris Cheney]], [[Andy Strachan]], [[Scott Owen]] |Studio = 5 |Singles = 26 |EP = 4 |EP link = Extended plays |Compilation = 2 |Comp link = Compilation albums |Video = 4 |Video link = Video albums |Music videos = 20 |B-sides = |References = Yes }} The [[discography]] of [[The Living End]], an Australian [[rock music|rock]] group, consists of five [[studio album]]s, twenty-six [[single (music)|singles]], four [[extended play]]s (EPs), four video albums and two [[compilation album]]s. The Living End's first exposure came from the single "From Here on In" in 1996. The song was released on their second EP ''[[It's For Your Own Good]]'' and received airplay on Australian national radio station [[Triple J]]. "From Here on In" placed at number 49 on the annual Triple J countdown, the [[Triple J Hottest 100, 1997|Hottest 100]]. The band's big break came in 1997, when the [[double A-side]] single "[[Second Solution/Prisoner of Society|Second Solution / Prisoner of Society]]" became the highest selling Australian single of the 1990s. The single spent 47 weeks in the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Top 50 Singles chart]]{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Living+End&titel=Second+Solution+%2F+Prisoner+Of+Society&cat=s|title=The Living End - Second Solution/Prisoner of Society (song)|publisher=australian-charts.com|accessdate=2008-08-13}} and charted in the top 30 of the United States' [[Hot Modern Rock Tracks]] chart. The Living End signed a contract with [[Modular Recordings]] and released their debut album, ''[[The Living End (self-titled album)|The Living End]]'', in 1998. The album charted at number one on the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Albums Chart]] and has since gone on to receive a four times multi-platinum certification from the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA), after selling in excess of 275,000 copies in Australia alone. Six songs from the debut album were released as singles and it remains The Living End's most commercially successful album. Their second album, ''[[Roll On (The Living End album)|Roll On]]'', contained the singles "[[Pictures in the Mirror]]" and "[[Roll On (The Living End song)|Roll On]]". It failed to live up to the success of their debut album, but still received a platinum certification from ARIA. ''[[Modern Artillery]]'' was The Living End's third album, released in 2003. The album achieved gold status in Australia, making it their lowest selling album to date. The band returned to the number one position on the Australian Albums Chart with their fourth album, ''[[State of Emergency (The Living End album)|State of Emergency]]'', in 2006. The album featured the band's first two top 10 singles in Australia since 1997's "Second Solution / Prisoner of Society" release. "[[Wake Up (The Living End song)|Wake Up]]" and "[[What's on Your Radio?]]" charted at number five and nine respectively. 2007 was the first year since 1996 that The Living End did not feature on the [[Triple J Hottest 100]], with only minor singles "Rising Sun" and "Til the End" released.{{cite web|url=http://melbourne.citysearch.com.au/music/1137596807893/The+Living+End|title=The Living End Editorial Review|publisher=Melbourne.citysearch.com.au|date=2008-07-20|accessdate=2008-07-30}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}{{ref label|jjj|H|}} 2008 saw the release of The Living End's fifth studio album ''[[White Noise (The Living End album)|White Noise]]'', along with the double A-side single "[[White Noise (song)|White Noise / How Do We Know?]]". The album debuted in its first week at number two on the Australian Albums Chart, achieving a platinum accreditation in Australia.
